observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed to strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of COA Circular Nos. 2009-01 and 2021-014 for the LGU’s e-Collection schemes in order to promote transparency and establish accountability over the public funds by:
Submitting a copy of the contract between G-Exchange and First Consolidated Bank, Inc; and Management Representation Letter;
Including an Auditability Clause in the LGU’s contract with the financial intermediaries;
Instructing the financial intermediaries to submit to the LGU a Certification of Deposit for all collection deposited to the LGU’s accounts with the AGDB; and
Requiring the financial intermediaries to post bond as required under COA Circular No. 2021-014.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct:

a. the BAC TWG to submit the lacking documents stated in finding (a) to the Audit Team and ensure that all of the eligibility requirements were submitted by the prospective bidder pursuant to RA 9184, its Revised IRR and GPPB issuances before issuance of Notice of Post Qualification to the concerned contractor;

b. the Municipal Engineer to evaluate carefully all the requests for the extension of time  by  the  contractor,  inspect  the  status  of  the  project  and prepare and submit the report thereon to the Municipal Mayor for his approval;

c. the Municipal Engineer to submit schedule of time elapsed and compute for the appropriate liquidated damages for the delays incurred and cause immediate refund thereof;

d. the Municipal Accountant to  draw  the  Journal  Entry  Voucher  (JEV) taking up the unrecorded  properties,  plant  and  equipment  and  the completed infrastructure projects in the books and  its  corresponding depreciation to state correctly the Municipality’s Property, Plant and Equipment and Government Equity accounts as of December 31, 2016.


e. the members of the Bids and Awards  Committee  and  Technical  Working Group to stop the practice of charging  honoraria  and  wages  of  Job  Order personnel out of savings from the fund established for specific purpose.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Accountant and other concerned officials to:

ensure that accounts are properly kept or monitored for easy reference of the agency or for other reporting purposes;
submit the lacking documents to avoid suspension in audit;
strictly adhere to Section 4.1.6 of COA Circular 97-002 in the granting of cash advances and that the officials be advised of the prohibition on the transfer of such.

Again, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:

Municipal Assessor to update assessment record and classification of real property and furnish the Municipal Treasurer copy of assessment rolls;



Municipal Treasurer to update the Real Property Tax Account Registry/Taxpayers Index Card for easy determination of amount due and collectible and furnish the Accountant of the updated certified list of taxpayers; 

Municipal Accountant to set up the receivables based on updated and certified List of Taxpayers and make the necessary adjustments on affected accounts;

Municipal Accountant forward the ending balance which pertains to uncollected prior years’ RPT/SET receivablesto the next calendar year and set upthe current year RPT/SET receivables at the beginning of the year and record any adjustments thereon accordingly;  

Municipal Treasurer devise strategies to collect all delinquent real property taxes and submit the list of real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected and the reasons for non-collectionsto Sanggunian to request for an assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for its collection as requirements in Section 269 of the IRR of RA 7160.

We again recommended the following:

the Municipal Budget Officer and GFPS ensure that the GAD Budget is equivalent to at least five percent of the total Annual Budget pursuant to R.A. 9710; 


the Municipal Mayor ensure that GFPS structures and compositions are in accordance with PCW-DILG-DBM and NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-01;

the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and GFPS establish and maintain GAD Database which will serve as a basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;

the GFPS ensure that the GAD Plan and Budget was reviewed and approved by the DILG Regional Office for integration in the AIP and funding.
